In SolidJS, you can scroll the browser to the top of the page when the active tab is set by using the `window.scrollTo()` method. You can trigger this within an effect or event handler.

Here’s an example:

### Example Code
```jsx
import { createSignal, createEffect } from "solid-js";

function App() {
  const [activeTab, setActiveTab] = createSignal("home");

  createEffect(() => {
    // Scroll to the top whenever the active tab changes
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: "smooth" });
  });

  return (
    <div>
      <nav>
        <button onClick={() => setActiveTab("home")}>Home</button>
        <button onClick={() => setActiveTab("about")}>About</button>
        <button onClick={() => setActiveTab("contact")}>Contact</button>
      </nav>
      <div>
        {activeTab() === "home" && <h1>Home</h1>}
        {activeTab() === "about" && <h1>About</h1>}
        {activeTab() === "contact" && <h1>Contact</h1>}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

### Explanation
1. **`createSignal`**: Manages the `activeTab` state.
2. **`createEffect`**: Reacts to changes in `activeTab`. Each time it changes, `window.scrollTo()` is called.
3. **`window.scrollTo`**: Ensures the page scrolls to the top. You can use `{ behavior: "smooth" }` for a smooth scrolling effect.

### Alternative: Using an Event Handler
If you want to handle it in the tab-change event handler instead:
```jsx
<button
  onClick={() => {
    setActiveTab("home");
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: "smooth" });
  }}
>
  Home
</button>
```

Both approaches work well, and the choice depends on whether you want the scrolling logic tied specifically to the tab change or globally.

