To set the active tab when an image is clicked, you can add an `onClick` event handler to each image. When clicked, the handler will update the `activeTab` state, which in turn will trigger any logic tied to it (like scrolling to the top).

Here’s how you can do it:

### Example Code
```jsx
import { createSignal, createEffect } from "solid-js";

function App() {
  const [activeTab, setActiveTab] = createSignal("home");

  createEffect(() => {
    // Scroll to the top whenever the active tab changes
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: "smooth" });
  });

  return (
    <div>
      <nav>
        <button onClick={() => setActiveTab("home")}>Home</button>
        <button onClick={() => setActiveTab("gallery")}>Gallery</button>
        <button onClick={() => setActiveTab("contact")}>Contact</button>
      </nav>
      <div>
        {activeTab() === "home" && <h1>Welcome to Home</h1>}
        {activeTab() === "gallery" && (
          <div>
            <h1>Gallery</h1>
            <div>
              {/* Images that set the active tab */}
              <img
                src="image1.jpg"
                alt="Image 1"
                style={{ width: "100px", cursor: "pointer" }}
                onClick={() => setActiveTab("home")}
              />
              <img
                src="image2.jpg"
                alt="Image 2"
                style={{ width: "100px", cursor: "pointer" }}
                onClick={() => setActiveTab("contact")}
              />
            </div>
          </div>
        )}
        {activeTab() === "contact" && <h1>Contact Us</h1>}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

### Key Points
1. **`onClick` Event on Images**: Each `<img>` tag has an `onClick` event that sets the `activeTab` to the desired value.
2. **Styling**: Use `cursor: "pointer"` to make it clear that the images are clickable.
3. **Reactivity**: The `createSignal` ensures that UI updates reactively when `activeTab` changes.

### How It Works
- Clicking an image calls the `onClick` handler, updating `activeTab`.
- The `createEffect` listens for changes in `activeTab` and scrolls to the top when it changes.
- The UI dynamically updates to show the content for the newly selected tab.

